MDF or particle board

00:49:45.020 --> 00:49:46.320
or whatever else, right?

00:49:46.320 --> 00:49:48.540
But they're still very proud
of their IKEA furniture.

00:49:48.540 --> 00:49:51.040
Similarly, my burrito
bowl at Chipotle,

00:49:51.040 --> 00:49:53.545
I care about it more
because I have hand-selected

00:49:53.545 --> 00:49:54.800
each and every single bean.

00:49:54.800 --> 00:49:55.415
SOPHIE EGAN: You
were a participant.

00:49:55.415 --> 00:49:55.914
Exactly.

00:49:58.605 --> 00:50:00.230
AUDIENCE: The other
thing that I wanted

00:50:00.230 --> 00:50:03.090
to comment on very quickly
was on the gluten-free stuff.

00:50:03.090 --> 00:50:06.142
I have a friend who has celiacs,
and he's commented both like

00:50:06.142 --> 00:50:07.350
on the pros and cons of this.

00:50:07.350 --> 00:50:08.250
He said, and one
thing that's great

00:50:08.250 --> 00:50:10.300
is I can go to every restaurant
that my friends go to

00:50:10.300 --> 00:50:11.420
and find something I could eat.

00:50:11.420 --> 00:50:12.836
He said, on the
other hand, no one

00:50:12.836 --> 00:50:14.460
thinks I have a disease anymore.

00:50:14.460 --> 00:50:16.085
They think I'm just
like a fad follower

00:50:16.085 --> 00:50:19.660
even though I've known I've
had celiacs for 15 years.

00:50:19.660 --> 00:50:21.500
So he said that was
also really frustrating.

00:50:21.500 --> 00:50:23.280
SOPHIE EGAN: That's
a great point.

00:50:23.280 --> 00:50:25.170
AUDIENCE: My bigger
comment and question

00:50:25.170 --> 00:50:28.170
is one of the things you
talked about a lot with work

00:50:28.170 --> 00:50:30.680
in particular was this
time crunch, that everyone

00:50:30.680 --> 00:50:33.262
feels very rushed all the time.

00:50:33.262 --> 00:50:34.970
I think it's actually
interesting to note

00:50:34.970 --> 00:50:36.761
that in the US, it's
not only that we spend

00:50:36.761 --> 00:50:39.450
200 more working hours per year
than we did 10 or 20 years ago.

00:50:39.450 --> 00:50:40.950
SOPHIE EGAN: About
a generation ago.

00:50:40.950 --> 00:50:42.720
AUDIENCE: A generation ago.

00:50:42.720 --> 00:50:45.230
But that we actually do so far
more than any other country

00:50:45.230 --> 00:50:47.030
in the entire first world.

00:50:47.030 --> 00:50:50.280
We just work way more,
and as you noted,

00:50:50.280 --> 00:50:52.010
have to spend a lot
less time cooking

00:50:52.010 --> 00:50:55.940
and eating than other first
world nations, similarly.

00:50:55.940 --> 00:50:57.720
Do you think that the
problem here is not

00:50:57.720 --> 00:51:00.280
simply one that can just be
dealt with in food policy

00:51:00.280 --> 00:51:03.450
but is simply a kind of
national epidemic of how

00:51:03.450 --> 00:51:05.895
we view productivity and
work-life balance in general?

00:51:07.569 --> 00:51:09.860
SOPHIE EGAN: Thank you for
that comment and a question.

00:51:09.860 --> 00:51:13.580
I absolutely think it
is that larger picture.

00:51:13.580 --> 00:51:17.770
And I get into this a little
bit in the book about how

00:51:17.770 --> 00:51:25.810
linked a lot of the policies are
in other progressive indicators

00:51:25.810 --> 00:51:27.250
that really affect eating.

00:51:27.250 --> 00:51:28.809
So for example,
also in that list

00:51:28.809 --> 00:51:30.350
of all the major
developed countries,

00:51:30.350 --> 00:51:35.240
we're the only one with
no paid maternity leave.

00:51:35.240 --> 00:51:39.650
And there's a whole bunch of
different social indicators

00:51:39.650 --> 00:51:43.110
or social measures
where what I'm

00:51:43.110 --> 00:51:46.160
seeing it's really interesting
is actually employers

00:51:46.160 --> 00:51:50.100
are sort of-- I this is
not the point of the book,

00:51:50.100 --> 00:51:51.950
but I'm seeing a
lot of different--

00:51:51.950 --> 00:51:54.770
especially in like Silicon
Valley type companies,

00:51:54.770 --> 00:51:57.520
where they're saying there
isn't a national policy of this,

00:51:57.520 --> 00:52:02.402
so I'm going to give six
months of paternity leave.

00:52:02.402 --> 00:52:04.610
There's some companies in
Germany where they actually

00:52:04.610 --> 00:52:08.600
shut off email after 6:00 PM.

00:52:08.600 --> 00:52:10.422
It just doesn't work.

00:52:10.422 --> 00:52:11.630
And they said, you know what?

00:52:11.630 --> 00:52:15.445
As a country, we want
people to go home

00:52:15.445 --> 00:52:16.570
and be with their families.

00:52:16.570 --> 00:52:17.903
We want them to be well-rounded.

00:52:17.903 --> 00:52:20.200
I also am really
fascinated by have

00:52:20.200 --> 00:52:22.360
we become less interesting?

00:52:22.360 --> 00:52:25.840
Do people do less
hobbies because they--

00:52:25.840 --> 00:52:28.850
it's sort of more
one-dimensional.

00:52:28.850 --> 00:52:34.210
We're so specialized and
so deep into the work.

00:52:34.210 --> 00:52:36.922
I'm like, well,
learn a language.

00:52:36.922 --> 00:52:38.380
I don't know, take
a ceramics class

00:52:38.380 --> 00:52:40.920
or just play with your
kid or whatever it is,

00:52:40.920 --> 00:52:42.750
sort of having more dimensions.

00:52:42.750 --> 00:52:46.280
I'm wondering how that--
I don't have the evidence.

00:52:46.280 --> 00:52:49.900
I don't know who's
studying that.

00:52:49.900 --> 00:52:52.380
Travel [? board ?]
or the leisure people

00:52:52.380 --> 00:52:55.820
out there who--
magazines and things,

00:52:55.820 --> 00:52:58.330
but that I definitely
think is very interesting.

00:52:58.330 --> 00:53:04.550
And I'm very intrigued
to see what levers

00:53:04.550 --> 00:53:09.140
can be pulled because this is
not about individually you suck

00:53:09.140 --> 00:53:10.800
because all you do is work.

00:53:10.800 --> 00:53:15.386
It's our individual choices
as not only with food

00:53:15.386 --> 00:53:16.510
but with how much you work.

00:53:16.510 --> 00:53:19.939
I mean, I work all the time
because I feel I have to.

00:53:19.939 --> 00:53:21.230
I have these deadlines to meet.

00:53:21.230 --> 00:53:22.890
And I have these
things I have to do,

00:53:22.890 --> 00:53:27.110
not because I love just
working all the time.

00:53:27.110 --> 00:53:29.680
So I think that the only
way this is going to change

00:53:29.680 --> 00:53:31.751
is when there are policies
that make it, again,

00:53:31.751 --> 00:53:34.000
the same way with food, that
make it not only socially

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:37.450
acceptable but socially normal
to sign off at a certain time

00:53:37.450 --> 00:53:40.610
or to eat during the workday,
as I mentioned, carving out

00:53:40.610 --> 00:53:43.850
that time for yourself, so
whatever those things might be.

00:53:43.850 --> 00:53:45.760
And I'm staying tuned.

00:53:45.760 --> 00:53:48.260
PETE: Let's all give Sophie a
great welcome and a thank you.

00:53:48.260 --> 00:53:49.160
[APPLAUSE]

00:53:49.160 --> 00:53:51.010
SOPHIE EGAN: Thank you, guys.

